CO2 is formed during the coal combustion process, and therefore the carbon control techniques are mainly categorized as (1) pre-combustion, (2) oxyfuel combustion, and (3) post-combustion (Bassano et al. 2020). In the pre-combustion CO2 removal pathway, coal is combusted during the presence of air/O2 to produce syngas, i.e., a mixture of carbon monoxide and hydrogen (Eq. 1), which is then used to fire the combustion turbine in a power plant (Leung et al. 2014). Ultimately, syngas undergoes, "water to gas shift" stage, and CO is converted to CO2, as shown in Eq. 2 (Osman et al. 2021). Afterward, CO2 is separated; it can be stored using various methods such as chemical absorption, adsorption, and membrane separation (Cao et al. 2020). The removal of CO2 in pre-combustion is much easier than the oxyfuel and post-combustion method because of the high concentration of CO2 in the syngas due to the water to gas shift stage (Osman et al. 2021).1Coal→gasificationCO + H2(syngas)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
